comment.author: 13267298@N00
comment._content: @ BigBean - although the Mitchell Library of the State Library of New South Wales does not specifically credit this to the Australian Photographer Frank Hurley, I can recognise his composition. And besides, someone has already tagged it "Frank Hurley" See more about his antarctic photographs here at the National Library of Australia: www.nla.gov.au/pict/explore/hurley.html To check my hunch that it was Hurley's work, I checked out the the National Library of Australia's collection of photographic images. They hold Sir Douglas Mawson's own collection of Antarctic Photographs. I think you will be startled by the brilliance of the image scanned directly from that: nla.gov.au/nla.pic-vn3255858 You will also notice there that the caption notes taken from Mawson's album puts the caption as: "A cavern beneath the coastal ice-cliffs with Whetter standing near entrance, Australasian Antarctic Expedition, 1911-1914" We can safely take it that Mawson, as the expedition leader, could best cpation the pic. Additionally, it is worth noting that the National Library of Australia holds the most extensive collection of Frank Hurley's glass plate negatives, although this is not one of them. @ Kyoba - I think that you will find, as I have, that the basic default position of most cultural institutions in Australia who have an online presence for their digital collections is that they will try to assert copyright ownership over just about everything they put up;whether it is in copyright or not, and whether or not the same image is held by a number of different institutions who may all make an attempt to assert copyright. In the case of images which are placed in Flickr's "The Commons" the responsible people at the cultural institutions have checked and found to the best of their knowledge that there is "No known copyright" - however this finding about the copyright of a particular image is not always changed back at the cultural institution's mothership website. You have identified a perfect example of this.
